title: For Sale:  Magazine Lee-Metford Mk. II
postcontent:
Up for sale is a mid-late 1890’s Magazine Lee-Metford Mk. II.   Overall it’s in pretty good condition, but has a few things that bear mentioning:
 
-          This gun is a civilian-manufacture model, made for British club target shooters and well-to-do officers that wanted a long rifle with extra care taken during fitting up.  This is evidenced by the lack of a rollmark on the action wrist under the bolt, where most Enfields have a royal cipher, year of manufacture, model, and name of the arsenal where it was made.
-          -This rifle has not been sporterized.  All the furniture is still there, barrel has not been cut down, all parts present.
-          -Volley sights are intact, and function.
-          -Magazine cutoff is intact, and functions.
-          -The bolt is lacks a safety (not missing, just not manufactured with one).   This was common for commercial MLM’s.
-          -Dustcover lugs are still present on the bolt.  Most of these were ground off over the years as Magazine Lee-Metfords were upgraded to newer standards over the years.
-          -Magazine cutoff intact, and functions.
-          -Exterior finish is excellent, both on the metal and wooden furniture.
-          -Bayonet bar is still present.
 
A few irregularities exist, which is common for guns that have spent 100 years in Afghanistan:
-          -The buttstock is from an SMLE or No. 4.   It lacks the long top tang of Long Lee butts.
Also, the bore is totally shot.  This gun was shot with corrosive ammo and not cleaned, and the barest traces of rifling remain.  The bore is pretty rough, no excuses.  I’ve shot the gun and can group rounds at 4”-6” at 100 yards, which is impressive considering the condition of the barrel.
 
This gun is the perfect restoration project, wall-hanger, or place-holder for the serious Enfield collector.  Willing to drive an hour from my home in Akron, OH to make the right deal, and I will also ship UPS at buyer’s expense.  This gun is classified as an antique by the ATF and no FFL transfer is required.   Rifle also comes with 10 rounds of HXP.
 
Feel free to message with any questions and to ask for additional pictures, I have plenty.
 
Thanks for looking!
